<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ops-customer-success-metrics">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>gtm-strategist</domain>
    <summary>Track customer health with scores, NPS/CSAT surveys, and leading indicator alerts. Predict churn 30-60 days early and intervene proactively with health dashboards and cohort retention analysis.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>customer-success</tag>
      <tag>metrics</tag>
      <tag>health-score</tag>
      <tag>retention</tag>
      <tag>nrr</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Customer Success Metrics and Health Scoring</title>
    <summary>Effective CS operations require a health score system that combines usage frequency, feature adoption, support sentiment, engagement level, and payment status. Monitor health distribution across account cohorts, track cohort retention curves, measure NPS/CSAT survey responses, and set up leading indicator alerts for usage drops and support escalations. Track expansion revenue from CS-driven upsells and Net Revenue Retention.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Without a health score and leading indicators, CS teams operate reactively on support tickets alone. A deliberate scoring system surfaces at-risk accounts 30-60 days before churn, enabling proactive intervention. Combining multiple signals (usage, adoption, support sentiment, engagement, payment) reduces false positives.</p>
      <p>NPS and CSAT surveys give qualitative context; cohort retention curves show actual behavior. Leading indicator alerts (usage drop over 30% in 14 days, support escalations, failed payments) are the most reliable churn predictors. Tracking expansion revenue and NRR proves that CS activities drive retention and growth.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>SaaS / subscription products with more than 10 paying customers and monthly billing cycles.</item>
        <item>Establishing a CS function or migrating from reactive support to proactive retention.</item>
        <item>Diagnosing why retention dropped without understanding which accounts are at risk.</item>
        <item>Measuring CS team impact: expansion revenue, accounts saved from churn, NRR improvement.</item>
        <item>Building a customer health dashboard as the single source of truth for CS priorities.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-purchase products with no recurring revenue — metrics apply to contracts/support satisfaction instead.</item>
        <item>Fewer than 10 paying customers — cohort curves are statistically unreliable; use qualitative feedback instead.</item>
        <item>Fully self-serve products with no human interaction — usage metrics alone suffice; add NPS only if you have onboarding touch points.</item>
        <item>Pre-PMF products where most customers churn regardless of effort — measure product-market fit first, then add CS.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="health-score-components">
      <p>A customer health score aggregates five weighted signals into a 0-100 scale. Each component captures usage frequency, feature adoption, support sentiment, engagement level, and payment status.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Compute customer health as: usage_freq (30%) + features_adopted (25%) + support_sentiment (20%) + engagement (15%) + payment (10%). Map each component to point values; use predefined lookups (e.g. daily usage = 30 points, weekly = 20) to ensure consistency. Bucket scores into four tiers: healthy (80 or above), stable (60-79), at-risk (40-59), critical (below 40).</statement>
        <rationale>A weighted formula ensures signals are comparable and reproducible. Predefined lookups make the score transparent and enable replication across multiple CSMs. The four-tier buckets match typical CS resource allocation: healthy accounts get nurture, stable get monitoring, at-risk get outreach, critical get daily review.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Health score calculation with weighted components">
        <description>A customer with weekly usage (20 pts), 3 core features adopted out of 5 (15 pts), neutral support sentiment (15 pts), medium engagement (10 pts), and current payment (10 pts) scores 70 pts, landing in the stable bucket. The CSM monitors this account monthly; if adoption drops next month, an outreach is triggered.</description>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Single-metric-only health system">
        <description>Using only usage frequency to determine health. A customer with daily usage but an escalated support issue and 30 days past-due payment appears healthy under this system but is actually at critical risk of churn.</description>
        <note>Single metrics hide high-risk accounts. Usage alone does not account for support friction, engagement burnout, or billing problems.</note>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Computing health score on a per-CSM basis without a canonical formula, leading to score inflation.</description>
        <reason>Inconsistent scoring breaks early warning systems. Formulaic scoring enables cross-team calibration and prevents subjective grade inflation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="monthly-dashboard-and-reporting">
      <p>A monthly customer health dashboard surfaces account distribution, at-risk and critical accounts, expansion-ready accounts, and key trend summaries.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Generate a monthly health dashboard showing: (1) health distribution table (count and % of customers, MRR and % of MRR, month-over-month change per bucket); (2) at-risk account list with assigned CSM, top risk driver, and action; (3) critical account list with assigned CSM and daily monitoring status; (4) expansion-ready list with upsell opportunity; (5) trend summary (NRR vs target, accounts resolved from at-risk, new accounts entering at-risk, expansion revenue). Publish the same day each month (e.g. 3rd of the month) so the CS team has one source of truth.</statement>
        <rationale>A standardized dashboard prevents tribal knowledge and enables rapid triage. Routing at-risk accounts to assigned CSMs with specific risk drivers enables targeted interventions. Trend tracking surfaces systemic issues (e.g. onboarding failure or feature churn).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Monthly dashboard with clear triage">
        <description>Dashboard shows 120 total customers: 80 healthy (67% of MRR), 25 stable (20%), 12 at-risk (10%), 3 critical (3%). The at-risk list identifies "Acme Corp" with score 42, assigned to Sarah, driver "Low usage 14d", action "Outreach scheduled", due Monday. Critical list shows "BigCo" with score 28, assigned to Sam, status "Daily monitoring — waitlist feature in progress".</description>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="No structured dashboard">
        <description>Health scores exist in a Notion database, but they are not aggregated. The CS team has no monthly ritual and no visible trend tracking. New CSMs spend a week "getting up to speed" on who is at-risk.</description>
        <note>Without a dashboard, at-risk accounts are discovered reactively via churn instead of proactively 30-60 days before.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="cohort-retention-and-nrr">
      <p>Measure actual customer behavior via cohort retention curves and Net Revenue Retention (NRR). Cohort retention tracks what percentage of customers from each signup month remain active. NRR above 100% is the North Star for SaaS.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Track cohort retention across all signup cohorts at the 1-month, 3-month, 6-month, and 12-month marks. Compute NRR monthly as (Ending MRR - Churn - Downgrade + Expansion - Upsell) / Starting MRR; target NRR greater than or equal to 100%. If any cohort's 3-month retention is less than 70%, or if NRR has declined more than 5 percentage points in a quarter, launch a post-mortem on onboarding, feature gaps, or pricing misalignment.</statement>
        <rationale>Cohort analysis isolates cohort quality. NRR encapsulates the entire customer lifecycle: it accounts for expansions and upsells that offset churn. NRR above 100% means the company grows revenue without acquisition, a sign of product-market fit. Drops in cohort retention or NRR are leading indicators of systemic product or onboarding problems.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Cohort retention with NRR tracking">
        <description>Signup cohort from Jan shows 85% retention at 1mo, 78% at 3mo, 72% at 6mo. Feb cohort shows 82% at 1mo, 75% at 3mo (cohort is slightly lower quality but within expected range). NRR this month is 108%, with $50k starting MRR, $2k churn, $6k expansion. Trend is healthy.</description>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Cohort data missing or stale">
        <description>Cohort retention is calculated only on request and cohorts are not tracked systematically. The team discovers a 30% drop in 3-month retention only when an analyst manually reviews data after a bad month.</description>
        <note>Late cohort discovery means interventions come 60+ days after the problem started. Automated monthly cohort tracking surfaces issues in real-time.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="nps-csat-and-survey-mechanics">
      <p>Net Promoter Score (NPS) and Customer Satisfaction (CSAT) surveys provide qualitative voice-of-customer feedback. NPS asks "On a scale 0-10, how likely are you to recommend us?" CSAT asks satisfaction on a 5-point scale.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Deploy NPS quarterly via email to all customers; require a minimum of 50 responses for statistical reliability. Deploy CSAT immediately after key moments (onboarding completion, support resolution, feature launch) with a 1-question form. Never run both NPS and CSAT on the same cohort within 30 days (survey fatigue drives abandonment). Analyze detractor verbatim responses for themes; assign top themes to product and CS backlogs. Track quarter-over-quarter NPS trend; a 5+ point drop signals a product or positioning problem.</statement>
        <rationale>NPS with fewer than 50 responses is statistically unreliable. Running both surveys simultaneously on the same accounts trains customers to ignore them. Detractor themes are early warnings of churn drivers. Quarter-over-quarter NPS trend is more predictive than absolute score.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="NPS with detractor analysis">
        <description>Q1 NPS deployed to 200 customers, 65 responses, NPS = 42 (promoters 35, passives 20, detractors 10). Top detractor theme: "Onboarding took 3 weeks, should be less than 1 week." Top promoter theme: "Killer reporting saved our team 10 hours/week." Action: Prioritize onboarding redesign; highlight reporting in next launch announcement.</description>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Running continuous always-on NPS surveys, polling every customer weekly.</description>
        <reason>Continuous NPS creates survey fatigue; response rate collapses after 2-3 weeks. Quarterly cadence is the sweet spot: frequent enough to catch trends, sparse enough that customers don't tune out.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="leading-indicator-alerts">
      <p>The most reliable churn predictors are operational signals detected in real-time: a 30% drop in usage over 14 days, a support escalation, or a failed payment. These alerts give the CS team 30-60 days to intervene before the customer churns.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Set up automated alerts for: (1) usage drop greater than 30% in a rolling 14-day window (vs. customer's baseline); (2) any support escalation (tagged "escalation" in ticketing system); (3) any failed payment (caught at payment processor webhook level). Route each alert to the assigned CSM with the account name, MRR, and alert reason. Measure alert accuracy (% of alerted accounts that churn vs. % of alerted accounts that stay) to calibrate thresholds. If false positive rate is greater than 30%, adjust thresholds upward.</statement>
        <rationale>Usage drop is the single strongest predictor of churn in cohort studies. A 30% drop in a 2-week period captures the inflection point before churned customers formally cancel. Support escalations signal customer frustration. Failed payments reveal customers with billing problems. Automated routing ensures no alert is missed.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Alert-driven intervention">
        <description>Acme Corp's usage drops 35% in 2 weeks. Alert fires; CSM Sarah receives notification "Acme Corp (MRR $2k) — Usage drop greater than 30%". Sarah calls Acme the next day, learns a key team member left, and discovers they need faster onboarding for replacements. CS delivers a 1-hour training call and usage recovers within a week. Account saved from churn.</description>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Only responding to customers who reach out via support; ignoring usage drops and silent warning signs.</description>
        <reason>Reactive CS misses 60% of at-risk accounts that decline silently without contacting support. Proactive monitoring surfaces issues 30-60 days before churn, when interventions are still possible.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="expansion-revenue-tracking">
      <p>CS teams are not just retention gatekeepers; they drive revenue growth through upsells and expansions. Track expansion revenue separately so CS contribution to ARR growth is visible.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Track two expansion metrics: (1) expansion revenue (dollars added by upsell/expansion from existing customers, net of downgrades/churn in that cohort); (2) NRR = (Ending MRR - Churn + Expansion) / Starting MRR. In monthly health dashboard, include expansion revenue closed by the CS team and list of expansion-ready accounts (healthy, high usage, feature adoption). Celebrate CS-driven expansions in team meetings to reinforce the revenue-generating role.</statement>
        <rationale>Expansion revenue is often overlooked but is critical to SaaS unit economics. Separating it from churn makes CS impact measurable: CS teams at Slack, Intercom, and Figma drive 20-30% of new ARR via expansions. Highlighting expansion-ready accounts gives CSMs a growth playbook. NRR above 100% becomes achievable through a combination of low churn and high expansion.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Expansion-revenue pipeline">
        <description>Monthly dashboard lists 8 expansion-ready accounts: StartupX (healthy, 5 team members, has asked about API access), LargeY (stable, heavy usage, likely to benefit from advanced analytics tier). CSM reaches out to each with a tailored offer. 3 of 8 convert to higher plan, adding $8k MRR expansion revenue. This expansion revenue is tracked separately and attributed to the CS team's pipeline management.</description>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Treating expansion as a product or sales function; CS team is measured only on retention/churn, not revenue growth.</description>
        <reason>CS teams closest to customers have the best visibility into expansion needs. When CS is excluded from expansion revenue tracking, they optimize for retention alone and miss revenue opportunities.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/health-dashboard.md" purpose="Monthly customer health dashboard template with distribution table, at-risk and critical accounts, expansion-ready list, and required actions."/>
      <template path="templates/metric-tracking.md" purpose="Monthly CS metrics tracking sheet: NPS, CSAT, retention, time-to-value, core feature adoption, NRR, cohort retention, and leading indicator alerts."/>
      <template path="templates/health.py" purpose="Python health score calculator: weighted formula combining usage frequency, features adopted, support sentiment, engagement, and payment status into a 0-100 score."/>
    </templates>
